<p class="head">2<sup>nd</sup> September, Continued</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">which is now the Only ground they Know, wh<span class="Gap">[&#8230;]</span> <span class="Gap">[&#8230;]</span> yet a few Beaver remaining<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  I am sorry to Ob<span class="AddHand-editors">[serve]</span> <span class="AddHand-editors">[that]</span> it is a general Complainte in Every Quarter of this De<span class="AddHand-editors">[pa]</span>rtment that they Cant find any Beaver no where, so that the returns from this Quarter will soon be on the decline<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[A]</span>n El<span class="AddHand-editors">[d]</span>er Brother of his Spoke next, who is a great Patison <span class="AddHand-editors">[of]</span> the Hudsons Bay people, and principal Chief of Osnaburgh Fort, where he may say that he is andeed, Master for, being invited to dine there last Spring, when I passed I saw him sitting at Dinner with us, and not Satisfied with getting a Share himself of Every thing that was on the Table, but he must be Shareing it among Several other Indians that was in the Room at the time without any One finding the least fault with him <span class="AddHand-editors">[for]</span> acting Landlord<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[H]</span>e said that he was now grown an O<span class="AddHand-editors">[ld]</span> Man, that his Fort, as he Called Osnaburgh, was too <span class="AddHand-editors">[far]</span> off, for him to go to it in Winter, therefore if I left Any One here, he would Come to them in Winter with Skins, as he Could not live a whole Winter, without getting drunk 3 or 4 times at least, but that I must leave a <span class="AddHand-editors">[gentle]</span> Man to deal with him, as he was above Trading with <span class="Gap">[&#8230;]</span></p>

